        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="col-lg-9">

            <!-- 1. Introduction -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="intro">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">1. Introduction</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>FTdx101 WebApp is a web-based control panel for Yaesu transceivers especially the FTdx101MP and FTdx101D but also works with the FTdx10. It runs as a small application on your shack PC and is accessed through any web browser — on the same PC, a tablet, or any device on your home network.</p>
                    <p>The application was written for operators who find the physical controls on the FTdx101 difficult to read or use, and for those who want a large, clean touchscreen-friendly display alongside their existing logging software.</p>
                    <h6 class="mt-3">Key features</h6>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Large, readable frequency displays with digit-by-digit mouse-wheel tuning</li>
                        <li>Full dual-receiver control (VFO A and VFO B)</li>
                        <li>Live S-meter, power, SWR, ALC, temperature, IDD, VDD, and compression meters</li>
                        <li>Real-time two-way sync — changes on the radio front panel appear immediately in the app, and vice versa</li>
                        <li>Band and segment selectors for fast QSY to CW, FT8, SSB, or RTTY</li>
                        <li>Optional real-time spectrum display and waterfall (requires an SDR connected to the 9 MHz IF output)</li>
                        <li>Integration with WSJT-X, JTAlert, and Log4OM</li>
                        <li>Built-in rigctld server so WSJT-X can control the radio through the app</li>
                        <li>UK and USA band plans</li>
                        <li>Full screen reader support — compatible with NVDA and Windows Narrator</li>
                        <li>Windows High Contrast mode support for all gauge displays</li>
                        <li>Customisable accessible labels (band names, meter names, control names) for any language</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 2. Installation -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="installation">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">2. Installation</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <ol>
                        <li>Download the installer from the <a href="https://github.com/mm5agm/FTdx101_WebApp/releases" target="_blank">GitHub Releases page <i class="bi bi-box-arrow-up-right"></i></a>.</li>
                        <li>Run the installer. .NET 10 is bundled — you do not need to install it separately.</li>
                        <li>A desktop shortcut and a Start Menu entry are created automatically.</li>
                        <li>The first time you run the app, Windows may show a <strong>Smart App Control</strong> or <strong>Unknown Publisher</strong> warning. Click <strong>More info → Run anyway</strong> to proceed. This warning appears because the installer is not signed with a commercial certificate.</li>
                    </ol>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 3. First-Time Setup -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="first-setup">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">3. First-Time Setup</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>Before the app can communicate with your radio you need to tell it which serial port the radio is connected to and what baud rate to use.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Open a browser and go to <code>http://localhost:8080</code></li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Settings</strong> in the navigation bar.</li>
                        <li>Set <strong>Radio Model</strong> to your transceiver: <strong>FTdx101MP</strong> (200 W, dual receiver), <strong>FTdx101D</strong> (100 W, single receiver), or <strong>FTdx10</strong> (100 W, single receiver — VFO B is hidden by default).</li>
                        <li>Set <strong>Serial Port</strong> to the COM port your radio is connected to. If you are unsure, go to <strong>Diagnostics → Ports</strong> to see a list of available ports, or check Windows Device Manager.</li>
                        <li>Set <strong>Baud Rate</strong> to match the radio's CAT baud rate. The factory default on the FTdx101 is <strong>38400</strong>. You can verify or change this on the radio under <strong>Menu → CAT Rate</strong>.</li>
                        <li>Select your <strong>Band Plan</strong> (UK or USA).</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Save Settings</strong>, then <strong>Test Connection</strong>. A green tick means the app is talking to the radio.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <div class="alert alert-warning py-2 mb-0">
                        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> If you see a red cross, double-check the COM port number and baud rate, then try again.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 4. Starting -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="starting">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">4. Starting the Application</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>Double-click the <strong>FTdx101 WebApp</strong> shortcut on your desktop. A small window opens confirming the server has started. The window must remain open while you use the app.</p>
                    <p>Open your browser and go to <code>http://localhost:8080</code>.</p>
                    <p>The main control panel loads. If the radio is powered on and the serial connection is correct, a brief <em>Initialising…</em> overlay appears while the app reads the current radio state. After a few seconds the overlay disappears and all controls reflect the current state of the radio.</p>
                    <div class="alert alert-info py-2 mb-0">
                        <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> <strong>Accessing from another device:</strong> If <strong>Network Interface</strong> is set to <code>0.0.0.0 (all interfaces)</code> in Settings (the default), the app is also accessible from any device on your local network. The Settings page shows the full URL for each network interface — bookmark one of these on your tablet or phone.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 5. Main Control Panel -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="main-panel">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">5. Main Control Panel</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body p-0">

                    <!-- 5.1 Top Bar -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="top-bar">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.1 Top Bar</h6>
                        <p>The top bar contains navigation links, external application buttons, and the radio power button.</p>
                        <p><strong>External app buttons</strong> (WSJT-X, JTAlert, Log4OM) appear if they are enabled in Application Setup. The colour of each button indicates status:</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-3">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Colour</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td><span class="badge bg-success">Green</span></td><td>Application is running and connected</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Yellow</span></td><td>Application is running but waiting for UDP data (WSJT-X only)</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><span class="badge bg-danger">Red</span></td><td>Application is not running</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                        <p>Click a button to launch the application. If it is already running, it is brought to the front. The <strong>WSJT-X</strong> button also shows a red <span class="badge bg-danger">TX</span> badge when WSJT-X is transmitting.</p>
                        <p class="mb-0"><strong>POWER button</strong> (top right) turns the radio on or off. The button is green when the radio is on and red when it is off.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.2 Meters -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="meters">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.2 Meters</h6>
                        <p>Seven meters are displayed in a scrollable row above the VFO panels:</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-3">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Meter</th><th>What it shows</th><th>Active when</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>SWR</td><td>Standing wave ratio</td><td>TX only</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Power</td><td>Output power in watts</td><td>TX only</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Compression</td><td>Speech compression in dB</td><td>TX only</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>ALC</td><td>Automatic Level Control voltage</td><td>TX only</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Temp</td><td>PA temperature in °C</td><td>Always</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>IDD</td><td>PA drain current in amps</td><td>Always</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>VDD</td><td>PA drain voltage in volts</td><td>Always</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                        <p class="mb-0">All meters update in real time at approximately 10 times per second. TX-only meters automatically read zero when the radio is receiving. If you find the meter scales inaccurate for your radio, see <a href="#calibration">Section 9 — Meter Calibration</a>.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.3 Power and Mic Gain -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="power-mic">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.3 Power and Mic Gain</h6>
                        <p><strong>Power slider</strong> — Sets the transmit power from 5 W to 200 W (FTdx101MP) or 5 W to 100 W (FTdx101D and FTdx10). Drag the slider to set the desired power level. The current value is shown to the right of the slider.</p>
                        <p class="mb-0"><strong>MIC Gain / Data Out Gain slider</strong> — Sets the microphone gain (0–100). When the radio is in a data mode (DATA-U, DATA-L, PSK, RTTY, or DATA-FM), the label changes automatically to <em>Data Out Gain</em>.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.4 Spectrum -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="spectrum">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.4 Spectrum Display</h6>
                        <p>The spectrum display is only visible if an SDR device has been configured in Settings. It shows a real-time spectrum and scrolling waterfall of the band around the current VFO A frequency.</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>Span buttons</strong> — Click <kbd>250k</kbd>, <kbd>500k</kbd>, <kbd>1M</kbd>, or <kbd>2M</kbd> to change the visible bandwidth.</li>
                            <li><strong>Click to tune</strong> — Click anywhere on the spectrum to tune VFO A to that frequency.</li>
                            <li><strong>Mouse wheel to tune</strong> — Scroll the mouse wheel over the spectrum to tune VFO A up or down in 1 kHz steps.</li>
                            <li><strong>Frequency crosshair</strong> — Move the mouse over the spectrum to see the exact RF frequency at the cursor position.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p class="mb-0">A status badge shows the current SDR state: <span class="badge bg-secondary">No SDR</span> <span class="badge bg-warning text-dark">Connecting…</span> <span class="badge bg-success">Live</span> <span class="badge bg-danger">Disconnected</span>.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.5 VFO Panels -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="vfo-panels">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.5 VFO Panels</h6>
                        <p>There are two VFO panels side by side:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><strong>VFO A</strong> <span class="badge bg-primary">Blue border</span> — the main receiver, present on all supported radios</li>
                            <li><strong>VFO B</strong> <span class="badge bg-success">Green border</span> — the sub-receiver, present on the FTdx101MP and FTdx101D. On the FTdx10 the VFO B panel is hidden because that radio has only one VFO.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p>Both panels have identical controls. All settings are independent — changing a control in VFO A does not affect VFO B.</p>
                        <div class="alert alert-info py-2 mb-0">
                            <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> <strong>FTdx10 users:</strong> When FTdx10 is selected in Settings, the VFO B panel and the VFO-B toggle button are removed from the main page automatically. They reappear if you switch back to an FTdx101MP or FTdx101D.
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.6 Frequency -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="frequency">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.6 Frequency Display and Tuning</h6>
                        <p>The frequency display shows the current VFO frequency in MHz to 1 Hz resolution (e.g., <strong>14.074.000</strong>).</p>
                        <h6>Digit tuning with the mouse wheel</h6>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Click on any digit in the frequency display. The selected digit is highlighted.</li>
                            <li>Roll the mouse wheel <strong>up</strong> to increase that digit, or <strong>down</strong> to decrease it.</li>
                            <li>Carry-over is automatic — scrolling 9 → 0 on the kHz digit also increments the 10 kHz digit.</li>
                            <li>The new frequency is sent to the radio approximately 200 ms after you stop scrolling.</li>
                            <li>Click anywhere outside the frequency display to deselect.</li>
                        </ol>
                        <div class="alert alert-info py-2 mb-0">
                            <i class="bi bi-phone"></i> <strong>On a tablet or phone:</strong> tap a digit to select it, then use the <strong>▲</strong> and <strong>▼</strong> buttons that appear below the display to adjust it.
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.7 Receiver Controls -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="rx-controls">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.7 Receiver Controls</h6>
                        <p>Each VFO panel has a row of dropdowns for the main receiver settings. All are two-way — if you change a setting on the radio's front panel, the dropdown updates automatically within half a second.</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Control</th><th>Options</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>Mode</td><td>LSB, USB, CW-U, CW-L, FM, FM-N, AM, AM-N, RTTY-L, RTTY-U, DATA-L, DATA-U, DATA-FM, DATA-FM-N, PSK</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Antenna</td><td>ANT 1, ANT 2, ANT 3</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Roofing Filter</td><td>12 kHz, 3 kHz, 1.2 kHz, 600 Hz, 300 Hz</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>AGC</td><td>OFF, FAST, MID, SLOW, AUTO</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>IPO/AMP</td><td>IPO, AMP1, AMP2</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>ATT</td><td>OFF, 6 dB, 12 dB, 18 dB</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>NR</td><td>OFF, NR1, NR2</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>NB</td><td>OFF, ON</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Auto Notch</td><td>OFF, ON</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Man Notch</td><td>OFF, ON</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Notch Hz</td><td>Slider 10–3200 Hz (applies when Man Notch is ON)</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.8 IF/AF -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="if-af">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.8 IF Width, IF Shift, and AF Gain</h6>
                        <p><strong>IF Width</strong> — Sets the DSP filter bandwidth: 200 Hz, 400 Hz, 600 Hz, 850 Hz, 1.2 kHz, 1.4 kHz, 1.8 kHz, 2.4 kHz, 3.0 kHz. This setting is persisted and restored on startup.</p>
                        <p><strong>IF Shift</strong> — Shifts the passband centre ±1000 Hz in 20 Hz steps. Drag the slider or use the keyboard arrow keys. The current offset is shown next to the slider. IF Shift is persisted and restored on startup.</p>
                        <p><strong>Zero button</strong> — Resets IF Shift to 0 Hz instantly.</p>
                        <p class="mb-0"><strong>AF Gain</strong> — Sets the audio output level (0–255). Drag the slider and release to send the new value to the radio.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.9 Band and Segment -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="band-segment">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.9 Band and Segment Selection</h6>
                        <p><strong>Band buttons</strong> — Click a band button (160m, 80m, 40m, etc.) to switch the VFO to that band. You can also navigate with the keyboard: <kbd>Tab</kbd> moves focus into the band group, then <kbd>←</kbd> / <kbd>→</kbd> move between bands and switch immediately.</p>
                        <p>Available bands depend on your band plan: UK includes 4m and 60m; USA includes the five 60m FCC channels.</p>
                        <p><strong>Segment dropdown</strong> — After selecting a band, a dropdown above the frequency display shows common operating segments for that band. Select a segment to jump directly to its standard frequency and set the appropriate mode:</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-3">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Segment</th><th>Example (20m)</th><th>Mode set</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>CW</td><td>14.025 MHz</td><td>CW-U</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>FT8</td><td>14.074 MHz</td><td>DATA-U</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>SSB</td><td>14.150 MHz</td><td>USB</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>RTTY</td><td>14.080 MHz</td><td>RTTY-U</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                        <p class="mb-0">The last segment you used on each band is remembered — when you return to a band, the dropdown re-selects your previous segment. On 60m, the dropdown shows named channels (e.g., CH1, CH2…) rather than generic segments.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 5.10 TX -->
                    <div class="p-3 section-anchor" id="tx-controls">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">5.10 Transmit Controls</h6>
                        <p><strong>TX button</strong> — Appears on whichever VFO is currently the transmit VFO. Click to start transmitting; click again to return to receive. The button turns red while transmitting.</p>
                        <p class="mb-0"><strong>Radio POWER button</strong> — Turns the FTdx101 on or off. The button shows <span class="badge bg-success">ON</span> or <span class="badge bg-danger">OFF</span>.</p>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 6. Settings -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="settings">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">6. Settings Page</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>Access Settings from the navigation bar. Changes take effect only after clicking <strong>Save Settings</strong>.</p>

                    <h6 class="section-anchor" id="radio-conn">6.1 Radio Connection</h6>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-4">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Radio Model</td><td><strong>FTdx101MP</strong> (200 W, dual RX), <strong>FTdx101D</strong> (100 W, single RX), or <strong>FTdx10</strong> (100 W, single RX — VFO B hidden by default)</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Serial Port</td><td>COM port the radio is connected to (e.g., COM3). Check Device Manager or Diagnostics → Ports if unsure.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Baud Rate</td><td>Must match the radio's CAT Rate setting. Factory default: <strong>38400</strong>.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Band Plan</td><td>UK or USA. Affects which bands and segment frequencies appear.</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <p>After changing the serial port or baud rate, click <strong>Test Connection</strong> to verify the radio responds.</p>

                    <h6>6.2 Web Server Settings</h6>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-3">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>Network Interface</td><td><code>localhost</code> — this PC only. <code>0.0.0.0</code> — all interfaces including LAN (required for tablet access).</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <div class="alert alert-warning py-2 mb-4">
                        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> After changing the network interface, save settings and restart the application.
                    </div>

                    <h6>6.3 SDR Spectrum Display</h6>
                    <p>The spectrum display requires an SDR receiver. On the FTdx101MP and FTdx101D the SDR is connected to the radio's 9 MHz IF output (rear panel RCA socket labelled <strong>IF OUT</strong>), giving a VFO-centred panoramic view of the band.</p>
                    <div class="alert alert-warning py-2 mb-3">
                        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle-fill me-1"></i> <strong>FTdx10 users:</strong> The FTdx10 has no rear-panel IF output. You can still use an SDR for spectrum display by connecting it to an antenna port, but the spectrum will show absolute RF frequencies rather than a view centred on your VFO frequency. The IF Frequency setting has no effect when used this way.
                    </div>
                    <p><strong>Supported hardware:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>SDRplay RSP1 and RSP series</strong> — requires the <a href="https://www.sdrplay.com/downloads/" target="_blank">SDRplay API v3 <i class="bi bi-box-arrow-up-right"></i></a> to be installed separately.</li>
                        <li><strong>RTL-SDR, Airspy, HackRF</strong> — drivers are included in the app installer; no separate installation needed.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Setting up the SDR (FTdx101MP / FTdx101D):</strong></p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Connect the SDR to the 9 MHz IF output using an RCA-to-SMA adapter and a short coax cable.</li>
                        <li>Go to Settings and click <strong>Scan</strong> in the SDR section.</li>
                        <li>Select your device from the dropdown.</li>
                        <li>Set <strong>IF Frequency</strong> to <code>9000000</code> (9 MHz).</li>
                        <li>Leave <strong>Sample Rate</strong> at <code>2M</code> and <strong>FFT Size</strong> at <code>1024</code>.</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Save Settings</strong>. The spectrum panel appears on the main page.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p class="mb-0">To remove the spectrum display, click <strong>Disable/Clear</strong> in the SDR section.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 7. Application Setup -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="app-setup">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">7. Application Setup</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>Access Application Setup from the navigation bar. This page configures the external application buttons and the WSJT-X UDP connection.</p>

                    <h6>7.1 External App Buttons</h6>
                    <p>Three buttons can appear in the top bar to launch external applications. For each button you can set:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Show / Hide</strong> — whether the button appears on the main page</li>
                        <li><strong>Button Name</strong> — the label shown on the button</li>
                        <li><strong>Command Line</strong> — the full path to the executable, including any arguments</li>
                    </ul>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-4">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>App</th><th>Default command line</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>WSJT-X</td><td><code>C:\WSJT\wsjtx\bin\wsjtx.exe --rig-name=WebApp</code></td></tr>
                            <tr><td>JTAlert</td><td><code>C:\HamApps\JTAlert\JTAlert.exe</code></td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Log4OM</td><td><code>C:\Program Files (x86)\Log4OM 2\Log4OM.exe</code></td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                    <p>Adjust the paths to match where you have installed each program.</p>

                    <h6>7.2 WSJT-X UDP Settings</h6>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Setting</th><th>Default</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>UDP Address</td><td><code>239.255.0.1</code></td><td>Multicast address WSJT-X sends status packets to. Must match WSJT-X Settings → Reporting → UDP Server.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>UDP Port</td><td><code>2237</code></td><td>UDP port number. Must match WSJT-X's port setting.</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 8. External Applications -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="external-apps">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">8. External Applications</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body p-0">

                    <!-- WSJT-X -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="wsjtx">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">8.1 WSJT-X</h6>
                        <p>The app integrates with WSJT-X in two ways:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><strong>CAT control via rigctld</strong> — the app runs a rigctld-compatible server on TCP port 4532. WSJT-X connects to this to control the radio (frequency, mode, PTT).</li>
                            <li><strong>UDP status sync</strong> — WSJT-X sends status packets (frequency, mode, TX state) to the app via UDP. The app uses these to keep VFO A in sync.</li>
                        </ol>

                        <div class="alert alert-info py-2">
                            <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> The default command line (<code>--rig-name=WebApp</code>) causes WSJT-X to use a separate configuration profile called <strong>WebApp</strong>. You must configure this profile once before it will work correctly. Your normal WSJT-X profile is not affected.
                        </div>

                        <h6>Configuring the WSJT-X WebApp profile</h6>
                        <p>Launch WSJT-X from the app's button (so it starts in the WebApp profile), then go to <strong>File → Settings</strong>.</p>

                        <p><strong>Radio tab:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Rig: <strong>Hamlib NET rigctl</strong></li>
                            <li>Network Server: <code>localhost</code> &nbsp; Port: <code>4532</code></li>
                            <li>PTT Method: <strong>CAT</strong></li>
                            <li>Click <strong>Test CAT</strong> — it should show green.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <p><strong>Reporting tab:</strong></p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>UDP Server: <code>239.255.0.1</code></li>
                            <li>UDP Server port: <code>2237</code></li>
                            <li>Outgoing Interfaces: <code>loopback_0</code> (or leave blank)</li>
                            <li>Multicast TTL: <code>1</code></li>
                            <li>Tick: <em>Accept UDP requests</em>, <em>Notify on accepted UDP request</em></li>
                        </ul>
                        <p class="mb-0">Click OK. These settings are saved in the WebApp profile and applied every time WSJT-X is launched from the app button.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- JTAlert -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="jtalert">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">8.2 JTAlert</h6>
                        <p class="mb-0">JTAlert does not use UDP. It reads WSJT-X log files directly. No configuration is required in this app for JTAlert to work. The JTAlert button in the top bar launches JTAlert and shows green when it is running.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Log4OM -->
                    <div class="p-3 section-anchor" id="log4om">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">8.3 Log4OM</h6>
                        <p>Configure Log4OM to receive WSJT-X decodes:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li>In Log4OM, go to <strong>Settings → Program Configuration → Software Integration → Connections</strong>.</li>
                            <li>Add a connection: Type = <strong>JT_Message</strong>, Port = <strong>2236</strong>, Enabled = <strong>Yes</strong>.</li>
                        </ol>
                        <p class="mb-0">Log4OM uses port 2236, which is separate from WSJT-X's UDP port (2237). Both can be active simultaneously.</p>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 9. Calibration -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="calibration">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">9. Meter Calibration</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>The calibration page lets you adjust the scale of each meter gauge to match your radio's actual output. Access it from <strong>Meter Calibration</strong> in the navigation bar.</p>

                    <h6>How calibration works</h6>
                    <p>Each meter has a table of calibration points. Each point maps a <strong>raw value</strong> (the number the radio sends) to a <strong>display value</strong> (what is shown on the gauge). The gauge interpolates smoothly between points.</p>
                    <p>For example, an S-meter table might have:</p>
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered table-striped w-auto mb-4">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Raw</th><th>Display</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>0</td><td>S0</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>120</td><td>S9</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>200</td><td>S9+20dB</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    <h6>Editing calibration</h6>
                    <ol>
                        <li>To add a point: click <strong>Add Point</strong>, then enter the raw and display values.</li>
                        <li>To delete a point: click the <strong>×</strong> button next to it.</li>
                        <li>To test during transmit: click the <strong>TX</strong> button on the calibration page and watch the meters respond in real time.</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Save Calibration</strong> when finished.</li>
                        <li>Click <strong>Reload From File</strong> to discard unsaved changes.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <p class="mb-0 text-muted small">Calibration is saved to <code>%APPDATA%\MM5AGM\FTdx101 WebApp\calibration.user.json</code>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 10. Diagnostics -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="diagnostics">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">10. Diagnostics</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>Access the Diagnostics page from the navigation bar. It is primarily useful when something is not working as expected.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>COM Ports button</strong> — Lists all serial ports currently detected on your PC. Use this if you are unsure which port the radio is connected to.</li>
                        <li><strong>CAT Status JSON button</strong> — Opens a live JSON view of every radio parameter the app knows about. Useful when reporting a bug.</li>
                        <li><strong>Live Meter Readings table</strong> — Shows the most recent raw value (0–255) received from the radio for each meter, the CAT command used to poll it, and the time of the last update. Rows flash yellow when a new value arrives. High SWR raw values are highlighted in orange.</li>
                        <li><strong>SignalR Event Log</strong> — A scrolling log of every radio state update received over the websocket connection, with millisecond timestamps. Use the filter dropdown to narrow the log to a single property (e.g., SWR, Power, S-Meter). <strong>Pause</strong> freezes the log; <strong>Clear</strong> empties it; <strong>Save…</strong> downloads the current log as a text file.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 11. Tablet -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="tablet">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">11. Using the App on a Tablet or Phone</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <p>The app is designed to work well on tablets and phones.</p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>Make sure <strong>Network Interface</strong> in Settings is set to <code>0.0.0.0 (all interfaces)</code>.</li>
                        <li>Note the network URL shown on the Settings page (e.g., <code>http://192.168.1.42:8080</code>).</li>
                        <li>Open that URL in the browser on your tablet or phone.</li>
                        <li>Use the browser's <strong>Add to Home Screen</strong> option to create a shortcut.</li>
                    </ol>
                    <h6>Touch-friendly frequency tuning</h6>
                    <p class="mb-0">On touch devices, tap a digit in the frequency display to select it. Two buttons appear — <strong>▲</strong> (increase) and <strong>▼</strong> (decrease) — which you can tap to adjust that digit.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 12. Keyboard Shortcuts -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="shortcuts">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">12. Keyboard Shortcuts</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <table class="table table-sm table-bordered table-shortcut mb-0">
                        <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Key / Action</th><th>Result</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td><kbd>F</kbd></td><td>Enter full-screen mode</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><kbd>Esc</kbd></td><td>Exit full-screen mode</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Click a frequency digit</td><td>Select that digit for editing</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Mouse wheel on selected digit</td><td>Increment or decrement the digit (with carry-over)</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Mouse wheel on spectrum</td><td>Tune VFO A up or down in 1 kHz steps</td></tr>
                            <tr><td>Click on spectrum</td><td>Tune VFO A to the clicked frequency</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><kbd>Tab</kbd> (in band buttons)</td><td>Move focus into the band button group</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><kbd>←</kbd> / <kbd>→</kbd> (in band buttons)</td><td>Move to the previous/next band and switch immediately</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 13. Troubleshooting -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="troubleshooting">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">13. Troubleshooting</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body p-0">

                    <div class="accordion accordion-flush" id="troubleshootAccordion">

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts1">
                                    App shows "Initialising…" and never clears
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts1" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>Check that the radio is powered on.</li>
                                        <li>Check the COM port in Settings. Go to <strong>Diagnostics → Ports</strong> to see available ports.</li>
                                        <li>Check the baud rate in Settings matches the radio's <strong>Menu → CAT Rate</strong> setting (default 38400).</li>
                                        <li>Click <strong>Test Connection</strong> in Settings.</li>
                                        <li>Make sure no other software (Ham Radio Deluxe, a second app instance) is using the same COM port.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts2">
                                    Frequency display shows 0 or does not update
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts2" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>The radio may not be responding to CAT commands. Click <strong>Test Connection</strong> in Settings.</li>
                                        <li>Check that no other application is using the same COM port.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts3">
                                    WSJT-X button stays red / not connected
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts3" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>Make sure you have configured WSJT-X's <strong>WebApp</strong> profile — see <a href="#wsjtx">Section 8.1</a>. This must be done once after a fresh install.</li>
                                        <li>Check that the UDP address in Application Setup (<code>239.255.0.1</code>) matches WSJT-X's <strong>Settings → Reporting → UDP Server</strong> address.</li>
                                        <li>Check the UDP port (default <code>2237</code>) also matches.</li>
                                        <li>Restart WSJT-X from the app button.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts4">
                                    WSJT-X CAT / Test CAT fails
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts4" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>Confirm WSJT-X Radio settings: Rig = <strong>Hamlib NET rigctl</strong>, Network Server = <code>localhost</code>, Port = <code>4532</code>.</li>
                                        <li>The rigctld server starts automatically when this app starts. Check the app is running.</li>
                                        <li>Check Windows Firewall is not blocking port 4532.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts5">
                                    Spectrum shows "No SDR" or "Disconnected"
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts5" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>For SDRplay: confirm the <strong>SDRplay API</strong> is installed and the <strong>SDRplay API Service</strong> is running (check <code>services.msc</code>).</li>
                                        <li>For RTL-SDR: check the device is plugged in and not in use by another application.</li>
                                        <li>Click <strong>Scan</strong> again in Settings and re-select the device.</li>
                                        <li>Verify IF Frequency is set to <code>9000000</code>.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts6">
                                    Meters appear to show incorrect values
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts6" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <p class="mb-0">The meters use a default calibration that may not exactly match every individual radio. See <a href="#calibration">Section 9 — Meter Calibration</a> to adjust the calibration for your radio.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts7">
                                    App will not start — "Another instance is already running"
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts7" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <p class="mb-0">Only one instance of the app can run at a time. Check the Windows taskbar for an existing instance. If the previous instance crashed and left a stale lock, restart Windows.</p>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#ts8">
                                    Cannot access the app from a tablet
                                </button>
                            </h2>
                            <div id="ts8" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#troubleshootAccordion">
                                <div class="accordion-body">
                                    <ul class="mb-0">
                                        <li>Check that <strong>Network Interface</strong> in Settings is set to <code>0.0.0.0 (all interfaces)</code>, not <code>localhost</code>.</li>
                                        <li>Check that Windows Firewall allows inbound connections on port 8080.</li>
                                        <li>Make sure the tablet is on the same Wi-Fi network as the shack PC.</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                    </div><!-- /accordion -->
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- 14. Accessibility -->
            <div class="card mb-4 manual-section" id="accessibility">
                <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
                    <h5 class="mb-0">14. Accessibility and Screen Readers</h5>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body p-0">

                    <!-- 14.1 High Contrast -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="high-contrast">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">14.1 Windows High Contrast Mode</h6>
                        <p>When a Windows High Contrast theme is active, the gauge displays adjust automatically:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Gauge needles are shown in bright <strong>yellow</strong> so they remain clearly visible.</li>
                            <li>Gauge backgrounds become transparent, preserving the half-circle appearance.</li>
                        </ul>
                        <p class="mb-0">To enable: <strong>Windows Settings → Accessibility → Contrast themes</strong>, choose a theme, and click <strong>Apply</strong>. No changes to the app are needed — it detects the theme automatically.</p>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 14.2 Screen Reader Support -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="screen-reader-support">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">14.2 Screen Reader Support</h6>
                        <p>All interactive controls have accessible labels that screen readers announce when you hover over or focus on them:</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-0">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Element</th><th>What is announced</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>Band buttons</td><td>Full band name — e.g., <em>"20 metres, radio button"</em></td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Band button group</td><td>Announced as a radio group; arrow keys move between bands</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Meter gauges</td><td>Meter name — e.g., <em>"S meter VFO A"</em>, <em>"SWR meter"</em></td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Frequency display</td><td><em>"VFO A frequency"</em> with current value in MHz</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Sliders, dropdowns, buttons</td><td>Their purpose — e.g., <em>"Transmit power"</em>, <em>"VFO A mode"</em></td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 14.3 NVDA -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="nvda">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">14.3 NVDA</h6>
                        <p>NVDA (NonVisual Desktop Access) is a free, open-source screen reader for Windows. Download it from <a href="https://www.nvaccess.org/download/" target="_blank">nvaccess.org <i class="bi bi-box-arrow-up-right"></i></a>. It works with Edge, Chrome, and Firefox.</p>
                        <table class="table table-sm table-bordered mb-3">
                            <thead class="table-light"><tr><th>Key</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td><kbd>Insert + N</kbd></td><td>Open the NVDA menu</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><kbd>Insert + Q</kbd></td><td>Quit NVDA</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><kbd>Insert + M</kbd></td><td>Toggle mouse tracking on/off</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                        <p><strong>Mouse tracking</strong> is the most useful mode for this app. When enabled, NVDA announces the name of whatever element is under your mouse cursor as you move it around the page — letting you identify every control without clicking.</p>
                        <div class="alert alert-info py-2 mb-0">
                            <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> NVDA reads abbreviations aloud. "SWR" is read as three letters. "PA" may be expanded to "Power Amplifier". The default labels in this app are written to avoid ambiguous abbreviations — see <a href="#custom-labels">Section 14.5</a> to customise them.
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 14.4 Narrator -->
                    <div class="p-3 border-bottom section-anchor" id="narrator">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">14.4 Windows Narrator</h6>
                        <p>Narrator is the screen reader built into Windows 11 — no download required.</p>
                        <p><strong>Toggle on/off:</strong> <kbd>Win + Ctrl + Enter</kbd></p>
                        <p>Narrator reads aloud the element that has keyboard focus. To navigate the app:</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Use <kbd>Tab</kbd> to move between interactive controls (buttons, sliders, dropdowns). Narrator announces each control's label and current value.</li>
                            <li>In <strong>Scan mode</strong> (<kbd>Caps Lock + Space</kbd>): use the arrow keys to step through all elements on the page, including meter labels and static text.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

                    <!-- 14.5 Custom Labels -->
                    <div class="p-3 section-anchor" id="custom-labels">
                        <h6 class="text-primary fw-bold">14.5 Customising Screen Reader Labels</h6>
                        <p>The text that screen readers announce for each control is stored in a labels file you can edit — for example to translate the app into another language or change any wording.</p>

                        <h6>How it works</h6>
                        <ul>
                            <li>The app ships with a default English labels file.</li>
                            <li>If you create your own copy at <code>%APPDATA%\MM5AGM\FTdx101 WebApp\labels.json</code>, the app uses your copy instead. Your file survives app updates.</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h6>Creating your labels file</h6>
                        <ol>
                            <li>Find the default labels file in the app's installation folder at <code>wwwroot\i18n\labels.default.json</code>. Open it with Notepad.</li>
                            <li>Copy the entire contents and paste them into a new file saved as:<br>
                                <code>C:\Users\&lt;your-name&gt;\AppData\Roaming\MM5AGM\FTdx101 WebApp\labels.json</code></li>
                            <li>Edit the <strong>values</strong> (the text on the right of each colon). For example, to use German band names change <code>"20m": "20 metres"</code> to <code>"20m": "zwanzig Meter"</code>.</li>
                            <li>Save the file, then press <kbd>F5</kbd> to refresh the page. The new labels take effect immediately.</li>
                        </ol>
                        <div class="alert alert-warning py-2 mb-0">
                            <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Do not change the keys</strong> (the text on the left of each colon, such as <code>"20m"</code>, <code>"swr"</code>, <code>"temp"</code>). Only change the values on the right.
                        </div>
                    </div>

                </div>
            </div>

